266// Owns and tracks the life-time of {ProtocolPromiseHandler} instances.
267// Each Runtime#evaluate, Runtime#awaitPromise or Runtime#callFunctionOn
268// can create a {ProtocolPromiseHandler} to send the CDP response once it's
269// ready.
270//
271// A {ProtocolPromiseHandler} can be destroyed by various events:
272//
273// 1) The evaluation promise fulfills (and we send the CDP response).
274// 2) The evaluation promise gets GC'ed
275// 3) The {PromiseHandlerTracker} owning the {ProtocolPromiseHandler} dies.
276//
277// We keep the logic of {PromiseHandlerTracker} separate so it's
278// easier to move it. E.g. we could keep it on the inspector, session or
279// inspected context level.
280class PromiseHandlerTracker {
281 public:
282 PromiseHandlerTracker();
283 PromiseHandlerTracker(const PromiseHandlerTracker&) = delete;
284 void operator=(const PromiseHandlerTracker&) = delete;
285 ~PromiseHandlerTracker();
286
287 // Any reason other then kFulfilled will send a CDP error response as to
288 // not keep the request pending forever. Depending on when the
289 // {PromiseHandlerTracker} is destructed, the {EvaluateCallback} might
290 // already be dead and we can't send the error response (but that's fine).
291 enum class DiscardReason {
292 kFulfilled,
293 kPromiseCollected,
294 kTearDown,
295 };
296 using Id = int64_t;
297
298 template <typename... Args>
299 Id create(Args&&... args);
300 void discard(Id id, DiscardReason reason);
301 InjectedScript::ProtocolPromiseHandler* get(Id id) const;
302
303 private:
304 void sendFailure(InjectedScript::ProtocolPromiseHandler* handler,
305 const protocol::DispatchResponse& response) const;
306 void discardAll();
307
308 std::map<Id, std::unique_ptr<InjectedScript::ProtocolPromiseHandler>>
309 m_promiseHandlers;
310 Id m_lastUsedId = 1;
311};
